In article <3q3qis$jhn@moe.cc.emory.edu>,
Philip D. Kartsonis <pkartso@moe.cc.emory.edu> wrote:
>I am planning to build a new Pentium-75 or P90 in the next few weeks and
>was wondering whether I should stick with IDE or go with a SCSI setup.

SCSI.  Definitely.  IDE now busmasters, but nothing beats SCSI's expansion
capabilities and raw throughput capabilities.

>The real
>question is whether or not one can boot Warp on a 2GIG scsi drive or
>not?  If so, how must one partition such a monster?

Warp will boot fine off a 2 GB SCSI drive.  I'd partition it as 100 MB for
Warp (make sure you create it at the start of the free space) and just make
the rest one big partition.  Warp will see all of it fine.

>I saw an ad in this month's OS/2 PRO about a scsi-III PCI card and 2GIG
>drive from Corporate Systems Center, what's the word out on these guys?

I don't know much about them, but I do maintain the PCI SCSI controllers for
OS/2 list, in which is contained all sorts of information on PCI SCSI con-
trollers for OS/2.  The next version of the list is (finally!) coming out
later today, and will be posted to comp.os.os2.misc and comp.os.os2.setup.misc.
The lists are also archived at ftp.netcom.com, in pub/ab/abe, and Web pages
of the lists exist at http://warp.eecs.berkeley.edu/pub/workbench/work.htm.

>Which enhanced PCI-IDE controllers are wise enough to access two IDE
>drives simultaneously (or is that a hopeless impossibility)?

As far as I know none do.  The CMD chipset is the closest, but it will not
allow simultaneous access to its two IDE channels.  I could be wrong here
(the PCI IDE list is still in its infancy), so someone please supply
specifics if I am.

>other PCI IDE or SCSI controllers are "Warpable" in the  $150-250 price
>range.

Have a look at the following SCSI controllers, all of which have Warp
drivers available:

QLogic IQ-PCI/10
Asus SC-200

Both of these are very good controllers (though I have a personal bias for
the QLogic because of their truly remarkable tech. support).
